Predicting credit card default with Taiwanese consumer data¶

Jacob Gull, Joel Casillas, Hugo Hernandez

October 24, 2018

Introduction¶

Credit risk assessment is important for creditors to be able make lending choices that benefit both the consumer and creditor. In the United States, credit scores from major credit reporting agencies are typically used to make lending choices, but machine learning can be used to make predictions for loan repayment as an alternate assessment of a borrower. This might be beneficial for making lending decisions for populations with low traditional credit scores or limited credit history.

The data we will be using is the default of credit card clients Data Set from the UC Irvine data repository, found here:

(https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/default+of+credit+card+clients)

This is data collected of customers default payments in Taiwan. It contains 24 attributes and 30,000 instances. The data was collected from April 2005-September 2005. We are going to be exploring the data and looking for any interesting datapoints in the data set.

Preprocessing¶

The data set was already pretty clean when we got it, so there wasn't much cleaning to do. No NaN values, empty values or spaces were found. We did however notice that the data set contained values 0 in the marriage column, so we decided to group the 0's and group them into 3's which stands for others in the data set. We also decided to rename the default feature because the original name was too long and complex.

We also created two new features, BILL_AMT_MEAN and PAY_AMT_MEAN which is the mean of the pay amount and bill amount for each instance.

In [14]:
df.loc[df['MARRIAGE'] == 0, 'MARRIAGE'] = 3
df.rename(columns={'default.payment.next.month': 'Default'}, inplace=True)
col = df.loc[: , "BILL_AMT1":"BILL_AMT6"]
df['BILL_AMT_MEAN'] = col.mean(axis=1)
col2 = df.loc[: , "PAY_AMT1":"PAY_AMT6"]

In [16]:
# This rocCurve plot will help us later with comparing classifiers
def rocCurve(aClf,X_test,y_test,modelName):
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, aClf.predict(X_test))
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, aClf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1])
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='Model({modelName}) (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.savefig('Log_ROC')
    plt.show()

We also decided to create this ROC Curve function that plots the ROC of a given model.

Recursive Feature Elimination¶

Based off the performance of our base classifier above, we decided to use recursive feature elimination to get the most important features from the data set to predict on. We created another Random Forest model, but this time using the top 5 most important features from Recursive Feature Elimination. To our surprise, the accuracy of the model was still pretty much the same. We tried using a different number of features and we noticed the more features we used, the better the model performed. Performance suffered when the number of features was reduced.

Ensemble Methods for Gradient Boosting & Voting Classifier¶

In [32]:
def gradBoost(X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,learning_rates):
    # learning_rates = np.arange(0.74,.76,0.001)
    for learning_rate in learning_rates:
        boost = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=20, learning_rate = learning_rate, max_features=2, max_depth = 2, random_state = 0)
        boost.fit(X_train, y_train)
        print("Learning rate: ", learning_rate)
        print("Accuracy score for training data : {0:.3f}".format(boost.score(X_train, y_train)))
        print("Accuracy score for TEST set: {0:.3f}".format(boost.score(X_test, y_test)))

Here we created a gradBoost method that will help us tune hyperparameters of our Gradient Boosting Classifier while also fitting it and prinitng it's score based on the different learning rates. This will help us see what learning rate corresponds to the best model.

In [33]:
def votingClass(X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test):
    extra_trees_clf = ExtraTreesClassifier(random_state=42)
    mlp_clf = MLPClassifier(random_state=42)
    log_clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
    rnd_clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
    svm_clf = SVC(random_state=42)
    voting_clf = VotingClassifier(
        estimators=[('xt', extra_trees_clf), ('mlp', mlp_clf), ('lr', log_clf), ('rf', rnd_clf), ('svc', svm_clf)],
        voting='hard')
    voting_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
    for clf in (extra_trees_clf, log_clf, rnd_clf, svm_clf, voting_clf):
        clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
        print(clf.__class__.__name__, accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))

We also made a Voting Classifier similat to the GradBoost one above to help tune parameters and get a better model.

PCA as a tool for dimenstionality Reduction¶

With PCA dimensionality reduction can be achieved by focusing as much of the data into the first principal components.

In [37]:
X2D = model.transform(X)

plt.scatter(X2D[:, 0], X2D[:, 1], alpha=0.2)
for length, vector in zip(model.explained_variance_, model.components_):
    v = vector * 3 * np.sqrt(length)
    plt.quiver( np.mean(model.mean_), np.mean(model.mean_ + v), color=['r'], scale=7)
plt.axis('equal')
plt.show();

The two red vectors represent the principal axes of the data, the length of the vectors explains how important the axis is in describing the data precisely. As in the graph above we can see the first principal component or the component in wit the larger magnitude in the y-axis direction is very important in describing the data.

In [38]:
pca = PCA().fit(X)

Choosing the number of components¶

In PCA is crucial to getting a estimate on how many components are needed to explain the data. Witht he explain variance ratio as a function with respect to the number of components we can se the amount of components needed to accuatly describe the data.

Incremental PCA¶

One problem with the preceding implementation of PCA is that it requires the whole training set to fit in memory. Incremental PCA (IPCA) can split the training set into mini-batches and is useful for large training sets, and also to apply PCA online. However the dataset is small enough that this is not required.

In [41]:
n_batches = 100
inc_pca = IncrementalPCA(n_components= 2)
X_copy = X
X_iPCA = model.fit_transform(X_copy)
for X_batch in np.array_split(X_copy, n_batches):
    inc_pca.partial_fit(X_batch) 
    X_iPCA = inc_pca.transform(X_copy)
print(X_iPCA.shape)

X_train_iPCA, X_test_iPCA, y_train_iPCA, y_test_iPCA = train_test_split(X_iPCA, y, test_size=.30)

Randomized PCA¶

Another option for larger datasets is to perform Randomized PCA, this is a stochastic algorithm which takes a quick equivalence of the first principal component. This algorithm is faster than Incremental PCA and PCA in general as long as d is smaller than that of n where the complexity is O(m × d2) + O(d3), instead of O(m × n2) + O(n3).

Ensemble Learning Methods & Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Voting Classifier¶

We will use a voting classifier to make better predictions, using "soft" voting and 5 classification methods. Soft voting returns an average of probabilities to choose a "winning" class.

In [45]:
def votingClass(X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test):
    extra_trees_clf = ExtraTreesClassifier(random_state=42)
    mlp_clf = MLPClassifier(random_state=42)
    log_clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
    rnd_clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
    svm_clf = SVC(random_state=42)
    voting_clf = VotingClassifier(
        estimators=[('xt', extra_trees_clf), ('mlp', mlp_clf), ('lr', log_clf), ('rf', rnd_clf), ('svc', svm_clf)],
        voting='hard')
    voting_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
    for clf in (extra_trees_clf, log_clf, rnd_clf, svm_clf, voting_clf):
        clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
        print(clf.__class__.__name__, accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))

Hard voting¶

We will experiment and see if we can obtain different results using "hard" voting. Hard voting is the simple case of "majority" voting.

In [47]:
def votingClassHard(X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test):
    extra_trees_clf = ExtraTreesClassifier(random_state=42)
    log_clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
    rnd_clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
    svm_clf = SVC(random_state=42)
    voting_clf = VotingClassifier(
        estimators=[('xt', extra_trees_clf), ('lr', log_clf), ('rf', rnd_clf), ('svc', svm_clf)],
        voting='hard')
    voting_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
    for clf in (extra_trees_clf, log_clf, rnd_clf, svm_clf, voting_clf):
        clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
        print(clf.__class__.__name__, accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))

We are using the same classifiers here as in the last experiment for consistency. The support vector machine classifier is returned to its default probability state (false).

Gradient Boosting¶

Our first ensemble method that we're going to use is Gradient Boosting. We are gonna be tuning hyperparameters trying to get a better accuracy.

Here I decide to use various learning rates to use for tuning the hyperparameters.

In [49]:
rates = [1e-3,0.05, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1, 1.5]

Here I tune the hyperparameter learning rate by looping through diferrent learning rates and seeing which ones results in a better accuracy. Than I'll use the best learning rate for the model to get the best accuracy for the model.

In [50]:
def gradBoost(X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,learning_rates):
    # learning_rates = np.arange(0.74,.76,0.001)
    for learning_rate in learning_rates:
        boost = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=20, learning_rate = learning_rate, max_features=2, max_depth = 2, random_state = 0)
        boost.fit(X_train, y_train)
        print("Learning rate: ", learning_rate)
        print("Accuracy score for training data : {0:.3f}".format(boost.score(X_train, y_train)))
        print("Accuracy score for test set: {0:.3f}".format(boost.score(X_test, y_test)))

We print the accuracy of the Gradient Boosting Classifier via the training and testing data based on the different learning rates.

Stacking Regressor:¶

Implementation of a stacking regressor to determine the best classifier from our previous classifiers in this project. The first method is the class StackingRegressor which takes in a list of classifiers and then can fit,predict, and score the classifiers. The ClassifierPCA method alters the classifiers to the dimensions of 2 to correlate with the pca dataset.

In [53]:
# Stacking regressor
# Params: array of classifiers
class StackingRegressor:

    def __init__(self, classifiers=None):
        self.classifiers = classifiers

    def fit(self,X_train,y_train):
        # Takes an array of training data for both X and y
        for classifier in self.classifiers:
            classifier.fit(X_train,y_train)

    def predict(self,X_test):
        # Takes an array of X to compute a y_predict
        self.predict = list()
        for classifier in self.classifiers:
            self.predict.append(classifier.predict(X))
        return np.mean(self.predict, axis=0)

    def score(self,X_test,y_test):
        # Takes a X_test array, y_test array, and for each classifier it gets the score,
        # and then performs the mean of the list of scores as it returns.
        scores = []
        for classifier in self.classifiers:
            scores.append(classifier.score(X_test,y_test))
        return np.mean(scores, axis=0)
    
def classifierPCA():
    finalboost = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=20, learning_rate = 0.25, max_depth = 2, random_state = 0)
    extra_trees_clf = ExtraTreesClassifier(random_state=42)
    mlp_clf = MLPClassifier(random_state=42)
    log_clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
    rnd_clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
    svm_clf = SVC(random_state=42)
    voting_clf = VotingClassifier(
        estimators=[('xt', extra_trees_clf), ('mlp', mlp_clf), ('lr', log_clf), ('rf', rnd_clf), ('svc', svm_clf)],
        voting='hard')
    voting_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    classes = [bag_clf,voting_clf,finalboost]
    return classes

Conclusion¶

Our experiments resulted with predictions within close range of each other. The base classifiers without PCA or the use of ensemble methods never reached an accuracy of 79%. We tried using dimensionality reduction and that did improve the accuracy of the models. We also used a Boosting Classifier, and that seemed to give us the better accuracy. At first, the Gradient Boosting Classifier would give us an accuracy around 78-79%. So we decided to tune the hyperparameters with a method we created called gradBoost. That function tests a few different values for the learning curve and so we are tuning the hyperparameters to get the best accuracy via choosing the best hyperparameters. After tuning the hyperparameters we managed to get an accuracy roughly around 81-82%. What was interesting was that Gradient Boosting, Bagging and the Voting Classifier performed very closely. At times Bagging performed better and in other instances, Gradient Boosting was better. Stacking gave a slight edge in prediction accuracy, and was our top performer. Overall, the top models averaged at around 82% accurate. It would be interesting to see how this model would perform with data from different countries.
